==================================================================
PHASE 0 — MANDATORY PRE-PROCESSING (MUST RUN BEFORE ANYTHING ELSE)
==================================================================
This phase MUST execute before any parsing, classification, or XML generation.
DO NOT skip, shortcut, or assume the input is small enough to skip chunking.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 0.1 — Call the Text Chunking Tool
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - Pass the COMPLETE, unmodified input file to the "Text Chunking Tool".
  - Parameters:
      - `text`                   = full input file content (do not trim or summarize)
      - `max_requests_per_chunk` = 20
  - The tool will return N chunks, each containing approximately 20 requests.
  - Each chunk will begin with the `=== SCENARIO : ... ===` header of its scenario —
    this is intentional and required for context continuity across chunk boundaries.
  - Wait for ALL chunks to be returned before proceeding.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 0.2 — Initialize Global Registry (Internal — No Output)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Before processing any chunk, create an internal global registry to track state
across ALL chunks:

  GLOBAL_REGISTRY = {
    scenarios:     {},   // key: scenarioName → { group, requests: [] }
    request_order: [],   // ordered list of all request IDs seen
    dynamic_ids:   [],   // request IDs classified as DYNAMIC
    static_ids:    [],   // request IDs classified as STATIC
    total_parsed:  0,
    total_dynamic: 0,
    total_static:  0
  }
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 0.3 — Process ALL Chunks Sequentially
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
For chunk 1, then chunk 2, … through chunk N:
  1. Parse all scenario headers (`=== SCENARIO : ... ===`) found in the chunk
  2. Parse all requests found in the chunk
  3. Classify each request (DYNAMIC or STATIC) using the rules in Section 2A
  4. Append results to GLOBAL_REGISTRY — do NOT reset between chunks
  5. Preserve original request IDs exactly — do NOT re-number

CHUNK CONTINUITY RULES:
  - Every chunk starts with a `=== SCENARIO : ... ===` header — use it to identify
    which scenario the requests in that chunk belong to.
  - If a scenario spans multiple chunks → merge ALL its requests into ONE scenario
    entry in the registry.
  - If a request ID appears in chunk 2 with the same scenario header as chunk 1 →
    attach it to that same scenario entry.
  - Chunk boundaries MUST NOT affect: scenario detection, request classification,
    ID numbering, or grouping.
  - Do NOT create duplicate scenario entries when the same scenario header appears
    in multiple chunks — always append to the existing entry.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 0.4 — Verify Global Registry Completeness
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
After all chunks are processed, verify:
  - ✅ All scenarios detected across all chunks are present
  - ✅ All dynamic requests are recorded with original IDs
  - ✅ Request order is preserved across chunk boundaries
  - ✅ No duplicate request IDs

DO NOT generate any JMX output until Phase 0 is fully complete.
